<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="318" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[159,772,1101,2018]" box="[159,298,1101,1127]" pageId="6" pageNumber="318">
<emphasis box="[159,298,1101,1127]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="318">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[159,772,1101,2018]" pageId="6" pageNumber="318">
A medium horseshoe bat with a forearm length of 52.9, 53.0 mm (
<tableCitation box="[398,495,1170,1196]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="7.[159,172,220,241]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="TABLE 2. External measurements (mm) and bacular length (mm) of 14 bat species recently collected at Lekoumou, Congo.Acronyms explained in the Materials and Methods section include means, ranges, and, where relevant, standard deviations. Numbers in parentheses refer to sample size where they differ from those stated in column 2" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/5FAA6645FF93C07DFF03FF23FC6EFEEE" pageId="6" pageNumber="318" tableUuid="5FAA6645FF93C07DFF03FF23FC6EFEEE">Table 2</tableCitation>
). The first phalanx of the third finger is relatively short (16.3, 
<quantity box="[646,759,1204,1230]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7899999999999998" pageId="6" pageNumber="318" unit="mm" value="17.9">17.9 mm</quantity>
); the second phalanx (27.0, 
<quantity box="[493,606,1238,1264]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.78" pageId="6" pageNumber="318" unit="mm" value="27.8">27.8 mm</quantity>
) is relatively long; the third metacarpal is 38.6, 
<quantity box="[618,732,1273,1299]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.87" pageId="6" pageNumber="318" unit="mm" value="38.7">38.7 mm</quantity>
in length. In the noseleaf, the horseshoe is broad with virtually no indication of a supplementary leaflet; the lancet has a rounded tip and is essentially straight-sided in one specimen and with slightly concave margins in the other. The sella has a shallow median constriction and a widely rounded anterior border; the superior connecting process is bluntly pointed (
<figureCitation box="[307,387,1547,1573]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="6.[816,829,1912,1933]" captionTargetBox="[814,1420,1417,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[806,1430,1384,1889]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIG. 4. Rhinolophus alcyone, HZM.16.40193, (A): superior connecting process; (B): sella; (C): baculum (dorsal view — left and lateral view — right). Scale for A and B = 2 mm; scale for C = 1 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943571" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3943571/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="318">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). There is one clearly defined groove in the lower lip. The skull is robust with a skull length (SL) of 22.82, 
<quantity box="[520,643,1615,1641]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.335" pageId="6" pageNumber="318" unit="mm" value="23.35">23.35 mm</quantity>
(
<tableCitation box="[661,755,1615,1641]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="8.[99,112,725,746]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="TABLE 3. Cranial and dental measurements (mm) of 14 bat species recently collected at Lekoumou, Congo.Acronyms explained in the Materials and Methods section include means, ranges, and, where relevant,standard deviations. Numbers in parentheses refer to sample size where they differ from those stated in column 2" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/5FAA6645FF9CC072FFFFFD2AFAA7FCC7" pageId="6" pageNumber="318" tableUuid="5FAA6645FF9CC072FFFFFD2AFAA7FCC7">Table 3</tableCitation>
). The anterior median compartments of the rostrum are well developed; the frontal depression is shallow. The canines are strong; the first upper premolar (P 
<superScript attach="left" box="[185,195,1748,1766]" fontSize="8" pageId="6" pageNumber="318">2</superScript>
) is relatively well developed and lies within the toothrow. The second lower premolar (P 
<subScript attach="left" box="[642,652,1801,1819]" fontSize="8" pageId="6" pageNumber="318">3</subScript>
) is small, but 
<taxonomicName box="[208,245,1821,1847]" class="Not" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" pageId="6" pageNumber="340" phylum="Myzozoa" rank="class">not</taxonomicName>
minute, and also lies within the toothrow. The baculum is 
<quantity box="[353,446,1855,1881]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3" pageId="6" pageNumber="318" unit="mm" value="3.3">3.3 mm</quantity>
in length and very distinctive (
<figureCitation box="[225,304,1890,1916]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="6.[816,829,1912,1933]" captionTargetBox="[814,1420,1417,1869]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[806,1430,1384,1889]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIG. 4. Rhinolophus alcyone, HZM.16.40193, (A): superior connecting process; (B): sella; (C): baculum (dorsal view — left and lateral view — right). Scale for A and B = 2 mm; scale for C = 1 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943571" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3943571/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="318">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). It has a thin, cylindrical shaft with a slightly expanded tip; the base is slightly bilobate and broad, when viewed laterally, and is deeply hollowed out, when viewed from below.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
